{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17660240","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17660240"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:21:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:21:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22763"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22763"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15710"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112027"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15710","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15710"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22763"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94093"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"10727"},{"type":"tags","id":"10728"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"45888"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45890"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112027","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112027"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-generation pedigree is shown below.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the inheritance pattern shown?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mitochondrial inheritance","Autosomal dominant inheritance","Autosomal recessive inheritance","X-linked dominant inheritance","Y-linked inheritance"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe pedigree demonstrates \u003Cstrong\u003Emitochondrial inheritance\u003C/strong\u003E. In this pattern, mitochondrial DNA is transmitted exclusively through the maternal line because mitochondria are inherited via the oocyte cytoplasm. The key features supporting this diagnosis include affected individuals of both sexes, transmission only through affected mothers, and absence of transmission from affected fathers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutosomal dominant inheritance\u003C/strong\u003E would show transmission from either parent with approximately 50% of offspring affected, regardless of parental sex. This pattern would not show the exclusive maternal transmission seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutosomal recessive inheritance\u003C/strong\u003E requires both parents to carry the variant allele, with typically 25% of offspring affected when both parents are carriers. The pattern would not show the maternal-only transmission characteristic of mitochondrial inheritance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EX-linked dominant inheritance\u003C/strong\u003E would result in affected fathers transmitting the condition to all daughters but no sons, while affected mothers would transmit to approximately 50% of all offspring. This differs from the exclusive maternal transmission observed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EY-linked inheritance\u003C/strong\u003E affects only males and shows strict father-to-son transmission, which is incompatible with the presence of affected females and maternal transmission in this pedigree.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe variable expression often seen in mitochondrial disorders results from heteroplasmy, where cells contain varying proportions of mutant and wild-type mitochondrial DNA.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mitochondrial DNA is inherited exclusively through the maternal line via the oocyte cytoplasm.","Both sons and daughters can be affected by mitochondrial disorders, but only affected mothers transmit the condition.","Heteroplasmy causes variable expression and penetrance of mitochondrial conditions within families."],"references":["Madibc68, CC BY-SA 4.0 \u003Chttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0\u003E, via Wikimedia Commons","Simpson DS. GeNotes. [cited 2025 Aug 23]. Mitochondrial inheritance \u2014 Knowledge Hub. Available from: https://www.genomicseducation.hee.nhs.uk/genotes/knowledge-hub/mitochondrial-conditions/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94093"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22763"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22067"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"22067","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22067"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/6xGd5QuCvTgZYMJMrkIajBBmA01WQG.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/6xGd5QuCvTgZYMJMrkIajBBmA01WQG.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":912}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94093","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94093"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-23T21:05:19+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-23T21:06:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15710"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112027"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"